1ï¸âƒ£ High-Level Answer (What interviewer expects first)

	Rails handles caching by storing frequently used data or rendered content in fast storage (like memory or Redis) so that repeated requests can be served faster without hitting the database or re-rendering views.

	Rails provides multiple levels of caching, from low-level data caching to full page caching.

2ï¸âƒ£ Types of Caching in Rails (MOST IMPORTANT)
	ğŸ”¹ 1. Page Caching (rare now)

	Stores full HTML page
	Served directly by web server
	Bypasses Rails completely

	ğŸ“Œ Mostly replaced by HTTP caching / CDN

	ğŸ”¹ 2. Action Caching (deprecated)

		Caches controller action output
		Still runs filters

		ğŸ“Œ Mention briefly, donâ€™t focus

	ğŸ”¹ 3. Fragment Caching (VERY COMMON)

		Caches parts of views

		<% cache @user do %>
		  <%= @user.name %>
		<% end %>


		Rails auto-expires cache when object changes.

		ğŸ“Œ Say:

		â€œFragment caching is widely used to cache partial UI sections.â€


	4. Low-Level (Data) Caching

	Used in models/services

	Rails.cache.fetch("users", expires_in: 10.minutes) do
	  User.all.as_json
	end


	âœ” Works with:

	Redis
	Memcached
	Memory store
	File store

	ğŸ“Œ This is what interviewers LOVE.

3ï¸âƒ£ Cache Stores (Backends)

		Rails supports multiple cache stores:

		| Store           | Use case             |
		| --------------- | -------------------- |
		| MemoryStore     | Single server        |
		| FileStore       | Development          |
		| MemCacheStore   | Distributed          |
		| RedisCacheStore | Production (popular) |



		config.cache_store = :redis_cache_store, { url: ENV["REDIS_URL"] }
	ğŸ“Œ Say:

	â€œIn production, Redis is commonly used as the cache store.â€

4ï¸âƒ£ Cache Key & Expiration (Important)


	ğŸ”¹ Cache Keys

	Rails uses:

	Object id

	updated_at

	@user.cache_key
	# users/1-20260110123456


	Auto-expires when record updates.


	ğŸ”¹ Expiration
		expires_in: 10.minutes


		Manual or automatic expiration.

